description: Keep Jira / ticket comments brief and scoped to the current work
alwaysApply: true
---

# Ticket comment discipline

When posting to Jira (or any external tracker) on the user's behalf:

- Keep comments **brief and to the point**. Summarize what landed in this
  repo and, if relevant, the single action another team needs to take.
- **Do not go beyond the scope of the current work.** No process
  recommendations, sub-ticket asks, epic restructuring suggestions, or
  unsolicited next-steps unless the user directed you to include them.
  If you think something is worth raising, **ask the user first** — do
  not add it to the comment preemptively.
- Prefer bullet points over prose for technical summaries. Cite APIs,
  tags, and filenames verbatim (backticks).
- Do not editorialize about responsibility splits, team ownership, or
  process unless the ticket conversation is explicitly about that.
- Avoid greetings, sign-offs, and filler ("Short version:", "Hope this
  helps", "Thanks!"). Get to the content.
- When the user asks you to rewrite a comment they removed, do not
  reintroduce removed content (asks, tangents) — they removed it on
  purpose.

Applies to: `addCommentToJiraIssue`, `createConfluenceFooterComment`,
`createConfluenceInlineComment`, GitHub PR/issue comments, and any
equivalent external-communication tool call.
